## When NOT to Use Specifications

### ❌ INCORRECT - Overusing Specifications

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Simple check doesn't need specification
export class SimpleCheckSpecification extends BaseSpecification<User> {
  isSatisfiedBy(user: User): boolean {
    return user.isActive() // ❌ NO - Too simple, just use user.isActive() directly
  }
}

// ✅ CORRECT - Use entity method directly
if (user.isActive()) {
  // ...
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Technical Specifications

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Technical query criteria, not domain concept
export class EventsCreatedAfterDateSpecification extends BaseSpecification<Event> {
  constructor(private readonly date: Date) {
    super()
  }

  isSatisfiedBy(event: Event): boolean {
    return event.getCreatedAt().isAfter(this.date) // ❌ NO - This is a technical filter, not domain rule
  }
}

// ✅ CORRECT - Use query directly or repository method
await this.eventRepository.findCreatedAfter(date)
```

## Performance Considerations

### ✅ CORRECT - Specification with Query Conversion

```typescript
// ✅ Efficient: Convert specification to query
export class FamilyFriendlyEventSpecification extends BaseSpecification<Event> {
  isSatisfiedBy(event: Event): boolean {
    // For in-memory checks
    // ...
  }

  toQueryCriteria(): Prisma.EventWhereInput {
    // ✅ Convert to database query for efficiency
    return {
      categories: { some: { isFamilyFriendly: true } },
      tags: { none: { isAdultContent: true } },
    }
  }
}

// In repository
async findBySpecification(spec: EventSpecification): Promise<Event[]> {
  // ✅ Use query conversion for database queries
  if (spec.toQueryCriteria) {
    return await this.findMany(spec.toQueryCriteria())
  }
  // Fallback to in-memory filtering
  const all = await this.findAll()
  return all.filter(event => spec.isSatisfiedBy(event))
}
```

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- Use Specifications for complex, reusable business rules
- Use Specifications when rules need to be composed (AND, OR, NOT)
- Place specifications in `domain/specifications/`
- Use Specifications for domain concepts, not technical filters
- Convert Specifications to query criteria when possible for performance
- Make Specifications composable using AND/OR/NOT operations
- Use Specifications for both validation and querying when appropriate

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't create Specifications for simple checks (use entity methods)
- Don't use Specifications for technical query filters (use repository methods)
- Don't put technical concerns in Specifications
- Don't overuse Specifications - prefer simple entity methods when appropriate
- Don't make Specifications depend on infrastructure

